There are several sorts of power tactics that leaders employ to influence subordinates, including: These strategies include the use of force or threats to exert control over others. Punishment, physical force, and the withholding of benefits are examples of coercive power strategies. Reward power strategies include the use of incentives or prizes to persuade others. Bonuses, promotions, and other types of positive reinforcement are examples of reward power techniques. These strategies include the use of official or lawful authority to exert influence on others. The proper use of power includes issuing commands, establishing rules and regulations, and using official titles or positions of authority. These strategies include the use of information, skills, or experience to influence others. Providing knowledge, resolving difficulties, and giving suggestions are examples of expert power strategies. Personal attributes, such as charisma, likability, and reliability, are used to influence others via the employment of referent power strategies. Relationship building, genuine interest in others, and inciting others to follow are examples of referent power strategies. Informational power strategies are strategies that use information to influence people. Providing data, numbers, and facts, as well as proof to support a stance, are examples of informational power techniques. 